<HEAD>

<TITLE>Tax Reform Commission Holds Five Public Hearings in September -- TRC
</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<center><i>
September 7, 1995</i>
<h3>Tax Reform Commission Holds Five Public Hearings in September</h3>
</CENTER>

<P>
 
<P>
<blockquote>
<B>WASHINGTON, D.C. -</B> The
National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform, chaired
by Jack Kemp, will hold five public hearings during September
as the group continues to gather testimony from taxpayers and
tax experts around the country about the need for reform. 
<P>
The commission's next hearing will be<B> Friday,
September 8, </B>in Los Angeles at the Museum of Natural History
at 900 Exposition Boulevard in South Central LA. The hearing will
begin at 9 a.m.  It is free, and the public is invited.  Local
citizens will present their views on the problems with the current
tax system and principles of reform. Other hearings will be held
this month in New York City in Harlem on Wednesday, September
20; at Howard University in Washington, D.C., on Tuesday, September
26; and inner-city Cleveland, Ohio, September 27.
<P>
By the end of September, the Tax Reform Commission
will have held 12 public meetings.  The commission is determined
to &quot;listen first.&quot; It is holding this series of public
hearings to learn from the American people their frustrations,
fears, and concerns with the federal income tax system  as it
develops its recommendations.
<P>
Senate Leader Bob Dole and House Speaker Newt Gingrich
have charged the 14-member commission with making recommendations
for a tax code that is &quot;flatter, fairer, and simpler&quot;
-- a system that will encourage economic growth and greater opportunity
for all Americans.
<P>
One of the most important aspects of the commission's
work is to talk with Americans from all walks of life -- small
business people, farmers, factory workers, inventors, and entrepreneurs
-- who make America work.
<P>
&quot;In all corners of the country, we have found
overwhelming anger and frustration with the current system, but
much more needs to be learned before Congress can move forward
with change,&quot; Chairman Kemp said.
<P>
The commission has been asked to study ways in which
the current tax code -- with its high marginal tax rates and thousands
of pages of rules, regulations, and red tape -- poses a barrier
to economic growth.
<UL>
<LI>It punishes the most dynamic forces for growth
in our economy -- the small business owners and entrepreneurs
who turn bold ideas into new businesses, new jobs, and new products.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>It discourages working Americans who are trying
to save for the future and to build a better life for themselves
and their families.
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>It is endlessly complex and confusing, costing
literally billions of dollars in lost time and effort.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The commission hopes to present recommendations that
will make the tax code more family friendly and create incentives
for saving and investment. It hopes to help guide the tax reform
debate toward changes that will reinvigorate entrepreneurship,
risk taking, saving, investment, and work effort. It hopes to
contribute to changes that will make America more competitive
and expand the nation's worldwide leadership in the 21st century
economy. 
<P>
Among the issues it is studying:  What are the implications
to the economy of a steeply progressive tax system? What is the
impact on economic growth of higher marginal tax rates? What do
people mean whey they say they want a &quot;fairer&quot; tax system?
 What do we mean by &quot;flatter&quot; tax rates?  &quot;There
are a lot of different views, and we want to know what the American
people think and what are the ramifications,&quot; Kemp said.
<P>
&quot;We are setting the stage for a 21st century
tax policy for America.  We hope that this series of hearings
will help all of us to learn more about the changes that are needed
to make better informed decisions about the hard choices that
lie ahead,&quot; Kemp said. &quot;If we can find the core, central
principles of a new vision for tax reform that includes everyone's
views, we can get this done. The American people -- and our children
and grandchildren-- will be the winners.&quot;
<P>
The commission expects to issue its recommendations
and report by the end of the year.
</blockquote><P>
    <P><P><font size="-1"><a href="/taxcom/prindex.html">PR Index</a> | <a href="/taxcom/">TRC Home</a> | <a href="/taxcom/reptoc.html">The Report</a></font></center><P></body>

