<HR>
<CENTER><H1>Young America's Foundation<BR>
10 Greatest Moments
</H1></CENTER>
<P>
<H1>1</H1><table align=left width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="sandy.gif" ALT="Sandra Day O'Connor" ><BR>
Supreme Court Justice <B>Sandra Day O'Connor</td>
</tr>
</table>
 
On August 14, 1983 a seventeen year old Afghan Freedom Fighter spoke to Young 
America's Foundation's summer conference. He told of his struggle, including suffering the loss of 
his family and being personally maimed by the Soviet troops that invaded his country.
<P>The following day, Monday, August 15, a group of American students, led by 
<B>Floyd Brown</B> of Washington and <B>Will 
Faron</B> of Florida, staged a protest against the Soviet invasion in 
front of the Soviet compound in Washington. Many news cameras were already on site to cover 
a hoped-for defection of the son of the KGB chief who was being held hostage in 
the compound. This combination of events garnered the conservatives national 
television coverage.
<P>Brown and Faron were arrested and prosecuted for their &quot;political&quot; 
anti-Communist demonstration even though no individuals were ever prosecuted for the many 
anti-South Africa demonstrations in front of that embassy. The D.C. government claimed it 
was &quot;untenable&quot; to prosecute 
<I>those</I> demonstrators. Hundreds of Leftists had violated the 
same law including the Kennedys, Jesse Jackson, Amy Carter, and former U.S. Attorney 
General Ramsey Clark, and yet not a single liberal was prosecuted! Brown and Faron were 
thrown into the D.C. Central jail with hardened criminals and denied any opportunity to plea bargain. 
<table align=right width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="floyd.gif" ALT="Floyd Brown" ><BR>
<B>Floyd Brown</b> is arrested outside the Soviet Embassy</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>Three other conservative demonstrators  Young America's Foundation staffer 
<B>Michael Boos</B>, Georgetown University Young America's Foundation leader 
<B>Bridget Brooker</B>, and George Washington University YAF leader 
<B>Michael Waller </B> filed a Federal action, <I>Boos v. Barry, 
</I>to halt the fifty year ban of demonstrations against Communist embassies. They lost at the district and 
appellate court hearings but the inconsistency of the government was gaining increased attention. 
<P>Finally, on March 22, 1988 the United States Supreme 
Court found that the young conservatives' Constitutional 
rights were violated. In a 5 to 3 decision written by 
Justice <B>Sandra Day O'Connor</B>, the Court held 
that &quot;our own citizens must tolerate insulting, and even outrageous, speech in order to 
provide adequate breathing space to freedoms protected by the 
First Amendment.&quot; 
<P>Brown's and Faron's convictions were overturned and 
the fifty years of the State Department protecting 
Communist governments from the free expression of the 
American people was over. The American Bar Association later called 
it one of the most important decisions of the Supreme Court.<BR>
<HR>
<H1>
2
</H1>
<P>&quot;NEWT! NEWT! NEWT!&quot; chanted the three hundred student leaders as longtime Young America's 
Foundation lecturer, and newly installed Speaker of the House, 
<B>Newt Gingrich</B> entered the Cannon Caucus Room for 
a triumphant Foundation banquet. The July 26, 1995 event was carried by all major television networks and 
was followed by the Speaker signing copies of his book,
<I>To Renew America, </I>for Young America's 
Foundation students.
<table align=right width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><img src="newt.gif" alt="Newt Gingrich">
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>The leader of the 1994 &quot;Republican 
Revolution&quot; praised Young America's Foundation and urged 
the students to &quot;help us get across to your 
generation that this revolution is about you.&quot; The event 
was organized by Foundation Vice-President <B>Ron 
Pearson</B> and also featured California Congressman 
<B>Christopher Cox</B><BR>
<P>
<BR>
<HR>
<H1>
3
</H1>
<table align=left width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="flags.gif" WIDTH=350></td>
</tr>
</table>
In early 1991 America was heading toward war in the Persian Gulf 
because of the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. Students seemed eager to support 
American troops and not follow the 1960s model when campus-based Leftists 
undermined America's armed forces. But college administrators were hostile to 
any patriotic sentiments. Some campuses, such as the University of 
Maryland, banned any display of the American flag!
<P>Young America's Foundation would have nothing to do 
with this &quot;political correctness&quot; and helped organize support 
for America's soldiers. An exemplary rally was held at Washington 
and Lee University by Foundation W&amp;L leader 
<B>Marc Short</B> and University of Virginia campus 
activist <B>Kate Obenshain</B>. They brought 
former Vietnam POW Admiral <B>Jeremiah Denton</B> onto campus for the first 
time since his imprisonment in the North Vietnamese &quot;Hanoi Hilton.&quot; The 
student response was spirited, with thousands of flag-waving students responding with 
the strongest patriotic fervor seen on campus in decades.
<P>
<BR>
<HR>
<table align=right width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="norman.gif" ALT="Normon Schwarzkopf" WIDTH=161 HEIGHT=243></td>
</tr>
</table>
<H1>
4
</H1>
A similar rally, but this time a post-Persian Gulf war 
event, occurred on February 13, 1992, organized by Foundation 
Director <B>James Lacy</B> and staffer <B>Peter 
Schweizer</B> at Chapman University. Gulf war hero General 
<B>Norman Schwarzkopf</B> addressed over 3,000 supportive students while many 
of the Chapman faculty protested outside. General Schwarzkopf 
put an end to the &quot;Vietnam war syndrome&quot; that cast 
American military leaders in the role of villains. Norman took 
the country, and the campus, by storm--giving a real 
life example of why he is called Stormin' Norman!<BR>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>
<H1>
5
</H1>
Young America's Foundation leaders <B>Frank 
Donatelli</B> and <B>Ron</B> <B>Robinson</B> established the now 
renowned Conservative Political Action Conferences (CPACs) in the 
mid-1970s when they were leaders in Young Americans for Freedom. 
<table align=left width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="ronron.gif" WIDTH=305 HEIGHT=253><BR> President Ronald Reagan
greets Young America's Foundation President Ron Robinson</td>
</tr>
</table>
<B>Ronald Reagan</B> was showcased at these conferences and its participants 
were looking forward to the March 1981 CPAC when newly elected 
President Reagan would again address CPAC.
<P>Young America's Foundation was a co-sponsor of the dinner, 
Foundation Director <B>James Lacy </B>was the master 
of ceremonies, and key Foundation supporters, including 
<B>John Engalitcheff</B>, were on hand for that electric 
night. Reagan chronicled the history of the conservative movement in one of his 
most moving speeches. Ronald Reagan has had a long and close affiliation with 
Young America's Foundation, but that March 20, 1981 evening at 
Washington's Mayflower Hotel was truly special.
<P>Nine days later, at a nearby Washington hotel, President Reagan was shot 
by John Hinckley. John Engalitcheff would later suffer a fatal stroke at a White 
House event with President Reagan. Mr. Engalitcheff would later become 
Young America's Foundation's most generous supporter by donating an eight 
million dollar bequest. But that CPAC dinner brought these key leaders together in 
the Conservative Movement's greatest night of celebration. <BR>
<HR>
<H1>
6
</H1>
The lecture program has always been the cornerstone of 
the Foundation's student outreach effort.  Over the years, these 
lectures have transformed America's campuses as Young America's Foundation lecturers 
have garnered increasingly large audiences.
<P><B>William F. Buckley, Jr.</B>, the &quot;godfather&quot; of the young conservative 
movement, consistently draws large and enthusiastic audiences. His speech at the University 
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill on April 20, 1993 was particularly notable.
<table align=left width="250" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="wfb.gif" ALT="William F. Buckley Jr." WIDTH=200></td>
</tr>
</table>
<P><B>Jesse Jackson </B>had just spoken at Chapel Hill on behalf of a controversial proposal 
to establish a separate African-American center. Over 750 students heard 
Reverend Jackson in what was, at that point, the largest event on campus. 
Conservatives needed one of their heroes to answer.
<P>One week later Bill Buckley was scheduled to speak in the same hall. 
Young America's Foundation supplemented its usual promotions 
with advertisements on a local <B>Rush Limbaugh 
</B>affiliate. Over 1,700 people crammed into the lecture hall, 
and hundreds more were turned away, as Bill Buckley's lecture 
won the audience over and became <I>the</I> event on campus that year!<BR>
<P>
<HR>
<H1>
7
</H1>
<table align=right width="250" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="thomas.gif" ALT="Clarence Thomas" WIDTH=279 HEIGHT=166></td>
</tr>
</table>
On April 30, 1996 Supreme Court Justice <B>Clarence 
Thomas </B>delivered a <I>Henry Salvatori Distinguished Lecture 
</I>for Young America's Foundation at South East Missouri State University. Over 
2,400 students gathered in the Show Me Center for an address that 
was carried by numerous radio stations, covered by C-SPAN, and won 
the hearts of all in attendance.
<P>Justice Thomas began the day meeting with individual classes and concluded 
it with a dinner at the Limbaugh residence in Cape Girardeau. Foundation 
activist, and recent staff intern, <B>Nathan 
Cooper</B> capped off his undergraduate years at 
South East Missouri State that evening. He had previously hosted 
<B>Michael Medved</B>, <B>Walter Williams</B>, <B>Robert 
Novak</B>, and <B>Dan Quayle</B>. <BR>
<P>
<HR>
<H1>
8
</H1>
<table align=right width="300" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="25th.gif" WIDTH=300><BR>
Former Foundation National Director, <B>Marc Short 
</B>(l), Foundation President <B>Ron Robinson </B>(c), 
and Foundation lecturer <B>Oliver North </B>(r) at the 
25th Anniversary banquet. </td>
</tr>
</table>
In November of 1995, Young America's Foundation celebrated its 25th 
anniversary with a banquet attended by the campus and national leaders that have made 
the Foundation the most effective student outreach organization in the country.
<P>Helping the Foundation celebrate a quarter-century of defending 
conservative principles on campus were key student leaders, longtime Foundation supporters, 
and several Foundation lecturers. The evening featured inspirational speeches by 
75th Attorney General <B>Edwin Meese</B> and Lt. Col. 
<B>Oliver North</B>, a patriotic song from Congressman 
<B>Dana Rohrabacher</B>, and the presentation of the 
<B>John Engalitcheff Award </B>to University of Pennsylvania professor 
<B>Alan Kors </B>for his dedication to fighting political correctness in higher education.  The banquet and speeches 
were carried to a nationwide audience by C-SPAN.
<P>Founded in 1969 by students at Vanderbilt University, Young 
America's Foundation has assisted hundreds-of-thousands of young Americans over 
the years.  At the banquet, the Foundation presented all guests with a 
special Anniversary Report highlighting the students, lecturers, and supporters that helped to build Young America's Foundation.<BR>
<P>
<HR>
<H1>
9
</H1>
<table align=right width="300" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="stan.gif" ALT="M. Stanton Evans signs The Theme is Freedom" WIDTH=300 HEIGHT=201><BR>
<B>M. Stanton Evans </B>(l) signs <I>The Theme is Freedom 
</I>for students.</td>
</tr>
</table>
National Journalism Center President <B>M. Stanton 
Evans</B> addressed a group of students, professors, and 
Foundation supporters who gathered in Chicago on April 25, 1992. 
Evans' topic, &quot;Religion, Politics, and the American Tradition&quot; was 
timely and the address was well received. What the intimate crowd 
that evening didn't know was that the reception they gave Evans 
would lead him to write his next major book, <I>The Theme is Freedom, 
</I>and that he would eventually deliver a similar lecture on more 
than twenty-five campuses and at several subsequent Foundation banquets.
<P>Evans' <I>The Theme is Freedom</I> became a major contribution to 
the debate that raged throughout the 1990s about the proper 
balance between government and religion and the role of our 
religious traditions in establishing modern freedom.<BR>
<P>
<HR>
<H1>
10
</H1>
<table align=right width="300" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="regnery2.gif" ALT="Harry Regnery" WIDTH=350><BR>
Jack Kemp </B>(r), <B>M. Stanton Evans </B>(c), and many others honored publisher 
<B>Henry Regnery </B>(l) at a Foundation-sponsored banquet in 1985.</td>
</tr>
</table>
On June 19, 1985 Young America's Foundation sponsored a special tribute to 
conservative publisher <B>Henry Regnery</B>. Over four hundred Washington VIPs, including 
<B>Jack Kemp</B>, General <B>William 
Westmoreland</B>, <B>William </B>and <B>Sophia 
Casey</B>, <B>John Chamberlain</B>, <B>James B. 
Taylor</B>, <B>Thomas Winter</B>, <B>M. Stanton 
Evans</B>, and ISI leader <B>Vic Milione</B> gathered to 
honor this longtime conservative leader at the Mayflower Hotel.
<P>Young America's Foundation republished Henry Regnery's 
<I>Memoirs of a Dissident Publisher </I>with a special salute from President 
Ronald Reagan for all those in attendance. Regnery was an 
early publisher of <B>Russell Kirk</B>, <B>William F. 
Buckley</B>, <B>James Jackson Kilpatrick</B>, <B>Frank 
Meyer</B>, <B>Willmoore Kendall</B>, and <B>Richard 
Weaver</B>. The celebration gave numerous students 
an opportunity to share in the great intellectual heritage of 
the Conservative Movement.<BR>
<P>
<HR>
<a name="sarah">
<P>
<CENTER><H2>New Scholarship Program Established in Memory of Longtime Supporter</H2>
<B>Sarah T. Hermann Remembered for Decades of Support for Higher Education</B>
</center>
<P>
<table align=right width="300" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="hermann2.gif" ALT="Sarah T. Hermann" WIDTH=230 HEIGHT=295><BR>
The Grover Hermann Foundation recently established 
a scholarship program with Young America's Foundation in honor 
of the late <B>Sarah T. Hermann</B>. </td>
</tr>
</table>
Young America's Foundation recently lost 
     one of its most dedicated supporters 
     when <B>Sarah T. &quot;Sally&quot; Hermann </B>
     passed away at age 80.  Mrs. Hermann, through the philanthropic foundation that 
she and her husband <B>Grover Hermann 
</B>established together, enabled Young America's Foundation 
to assist tens-of-thousands of students over the years.
<P>In 1992, as president of the Grover Hermann Foundation,  Mrs. Hermann established 
with Young America's Foundation an annual lecture series bearing her late husband's name.  
Her generosity provided Young America's Foundation with the funds needed to send 
outstanding lecturers such as <B>Dinesh 
D'Souza</B>, <B>Angela &quot;Bay&quot; 
Buchanan</B>, <B>Edwin Meese</B>, and <B>Michael Medved 
</B>to speak to students under the <I>Grover Hermann 
Freedom Lecture Series</I>.  
<table align=left
 width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="roned.gif" ALT="Ron Robinson and Edwin Meese" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=143><BR>
Foundation President <B>Ron Robinson </B>meets 
with 1994-95 <I>Hermann Lecturer </I><B>Edwin Meese 
</B>in the Grover Hermann Freedom Library.  The Library 
was established through a generous grant in 1990.</td>
</tr>
</table>
As <I>Hermann 
Lecturers</I>, Mr. D'Souza and Ms. Buchanan met with 
Mrs. Hermann at her Pebble Beach, California home to discuss their campus appearances and 
conversations with students during the year.  &quot;The 
value of this lecture series on America's campuses cannot be overestimated,&quot; notes 
Foundation President <B>Ron Robinson</B>.  &quot;In establishing 
this program, Sally Hermann and the Grover Hermann 
Foundation ensured that the values and principles that made our country 
great  freedom, liberty, moral virtue and decency  will always have a 
voice on our nation's colleges and universities.  She will be greatly 
missed, but due to her lifelong generosity, she will never be forgotten.&quot; 
<P>Born May 26, 1915 in Fulton, Missouri, Sarah Hermann 
attended William Woods College and then went on to work for the 
American-Marietta Co. where she met Grover Hermann, 
the founder of the company and her future husband. 
 The two were married in 1945 and founded the Grover 
Hermann Foundation in the 1950s.  Mrs. Hermann became the foundation's president upon the death of her 
husband in 1979.  The Hermanns were early supporters 
of the conservative movement, and continued their support 
throughout their lives.  In addition to her support 
of Young America's Foundation programs, Mrs. Hermann also served as an Honorary Trustee 
of the Heritage Foundation.
<table align=left
 width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="medved.gif" ALT="Michael Medved" WIDTH=200 ><BR>
Film critic <B>Michael Medved</B>, the 1995-96 <I>Hermann 
Lecturer</I>, notes that his Foundation 
appearances have &quot;enhanced my work and enriched my life during the 
period of our association....  I'm glad you're there, fighting the 
good fight and doing such brave work in challenging the tyranny 
of political correctness.&quot;
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>Sarah Hermann was recognized by friends and associates as a 
committed philanthropist.  <B>Todd Lueders</B>, director of the 
Community Foundation for Monterey County  an organization to which 
Mrs. Hermann served as a Trustee  described her as representing 
&quot;absolutely the best kind of philanthropy.  She was quiet, understated 
and careful in her foundation and personal giving.  She assessed 
which agencies do good work....  That was all part of her gracious[ness].&quot;
<P>Upon her death, the Grover Hermann Foundation desired 
to honor Sarah Hermann with a gift to an appropriate organization.  
Mrs. Hermann's sister, <B>Harriet Thurmond</B>,  
suggested Young America's Foundation, and the resulting gift led to the establishment of 
the <I>Sarah T. Hermann Scholarship </I>intern 
program. 
<P>&quot;Mrs. Hermann has been a loyal supporter 
of Young America's Foundation and the Conservative Movement for decades,&quot; adds Mr. Robinson. 
 &quot;She was a kind friend and a gracious host, 
and was always a leader in improving America's colleges and universities.  We are proud to 
be selected by her family to help commemorate her accomplishments with a program that 
will achieve one of her own goals:  bringing the message of freedom to 
America's college students.&quot;<BR>
<table align=right
 width="500" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="dsouza.gif" ALT="Dinesh D'Souza" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=244></td><td>
&quot;<B>Dinesh D'Souza's </B><I>Grover Hermann 
Lecture </I>at Swarthmore literally revolutionized 
my college.  His was the first conservative or 
free market lecture there in <I>at least </I>four 
years. His lecture breathed life into our 
struggling conservative organization and set the 
wheels in motion that would enable us to bring <I>seven 
</I>Foundation speakers to campus in the next school year.  Without Mr. 
D'Souza's <I>Hermann Lecture</I>, my four years at Swarthmore would have been 
nothing but a one-sided barrage of Leftist indoctrination.  I cannot thank 
<B>Sarah Hermann </B>enough for helping to save my education.&quot;    
 -- <B>Matt Schenk</B>, 1995 Swarthmore College graduate. <BR></td>
</tr>
</table>


