<HR>
<CENTER><B><I>Sarah T. Hermann Scholarship </I>Intern Program Launched by Foundation</B><BR></CENTER>
Young America's Foundation is pleased to announce 
     the <I>Sarah T. Hermann Scholarship </I>intern program, 
     created in memory of one of the Foundation's most 
     loyal supporters.  The purpose of this program is 
to develop a cadre of young conservative leaders for our 
country through the hands-on experience that only an internship 
can provide.  The program will also provide direct financial 
assistance to these interns, who will be chosen from among 
the Foundation's finest student leaders.
<P>Young America's Foundation will seek out 
motivated students to serve as semester- or summer-long interns.  
Student leaders selected as <I>Hermann </I>interns will conduct 
original research on campus issues to be published and distributed 
as issue briefs.  <I>Sarah T. Hermann </I>interns will also be involved 
in planning Foundation conferences and lectures, and will, in 
the course 
of their duties, be encouraged to become more involved in 
the Conservative Movement and expand their knowledge 
of conservative and free market ideas and principles.
<P>In the past, many of the Foundation's most 
dedicated student activists have been former interns.  Now, through 
the generosity of the Grover Hermann Foundation, 
Young America's Foundation will be able to greatly increase 
the number of students participating as Foundation interns, 
and will simultaneously help to strengthen America's next 
generation of leaders.
<P>For more information on this program, please call 
the Foundation at (703) 318-9608 or write to:  <I>Sarah 
T. Hermann Scholarship Program</I>, Young America's 
Foundation, F.M. Kirby Freedom Center, 110 Elden Street, 
Herndon, Virginia, 20170.<BR>
<P>
<HR>
<a name="cspan">
<P>
<B><CENTER>C-SPAN Airs Extensive Coverage of Foundation Programs</CENTER></b>
<BR>
Lectures by D'Souza, Thomas, Medved, Reed, Phillips, LaPierre, Abrams, Williams, and Evans Broadcast Nationwide</B><BR>
If you watch C-SPAN, you have probably 
     seen quite a bit from Young America's 
     Foundation over the past few months.  
<table align=left
 width="300" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="cspan2.gif" ALT="CSPAN camera" WIDTH=171 HEIGHT=120></td><td><B>C-SPAN</B> has taped ten Foundation events in the past few 
months, and has aired them almost forty different times.</td>
</tr>
</table>
     Since April, 1996 ten Foundation events have been covered by C-SPAN, and the 
cable network has aired these programs on almost forty separate occasions.  Many of these 
events  which include Foundation conferences, lecture series speakers, and Foundation 
staff appearing on C-SPAN programming  have elicited an outpouring of positive response: 
 hundreds of letters and phone calls of support for the Foundation programs.
<table align=right
 width="300" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="cspan1.gif" ALT="CSPAN camera" WIDTH=171 HEIGHT=120><BR>C-SPAN crews travelled to Cape Girardeau, Missouri to cover 
a <I>Henry Salvatori Distinguished Lecture </I>by Justice 
<B>Clarence Thomas</td>
</B>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<P>Most recently, Foundation Conference Director 
<B>Kristen Kingsley </B>appeared on C-SPAN's <I>Washington 
Journal</I>, debating current policy issues.  Earlier this summer, Miss 
Kingsly  also appeared on C-SPAN when she delivered the welcoming address for 
the Foundation's 18th annual National Conservative Student Conference.  This conference 
received more C-SPAN coverage than any previous 
year's with seven lecturers being taped and broadcast several times in the 
weeks following the program.  
<table align=left
 width="300" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="kristen.gif" WIDTH=251 HEIGHT=249><BR>
Foundation Conference Director <B>Kristen 
Kingsley</B>, and seven other Foundation lecturers, were 
broadcast nationwide by C-SPAN during this year's 
summer conference.  Miss Kingsley was also recently featured on 
C-SPAN's <I>Washington Journal</I>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Covered speakers included 
<B>Michael Medved</B>, <B>Ralph Reed</B>, <B>Howard 
Phillips</B>, <B>Wayne LaPierre</B>, <B>Elliot 
Abrams</B>, <B>Armstrong Williams</B>, and <B>M. Stanton 
Evans</B>.  Each lecture was aired by C-SPAN at least five times.
<P>C-SPAN was also present at two important Young America's 
Foundation lectures during the spring, 1996 semester. 
 In late April, Supreme Court Justice <B>Clarence 
Thomas</B>' <I>Henry Salvatori Distinguished Lecture 
</I>was covered by C-SPAN and subsequently aired before a nationwide audience.  C-SPAN sent 
its filming crew on-location to the lecture site in Cape Girardeau, Missouri, 
giving testament to the importance with which the Foundation's lecture program is viewed.
<P>Earlier in April, <B>Dinesh D'Souza</B>'s 
Foundation lecture at the California regional 
conference was taped by C-SPAN for their feature 
program, <I>Booknotes</I>.  In addition to airing his lecture 
on multiculturalism and affirmative action, Mr. D'Souza's latest book, 
<I>The End of Racism</I>, was profiled.
<P>The Foundation's efforts to fight the Leftist monopoly on our nation's campuses is a 
battle that many Americans should be and are concerned about.  When Young America's 
Foundation programs attract C-SPAN coverage, it enables the Foundation to bring its message 
to an audience of millions, multiplying the effectiveness of the Conservative 
Movement's most aggressive outreach program.     
