<p><p>


<a name="reform"><center><h3>Campus Reform Seminar Scheduled for March 30<br></center></h3></a>

Does your campus lack a balanced speakers program? Do you want to bring a prominent conservative figure to your campus, but just don't know how?
<P>The staff of Young America's Foundation is holding a special training session for interested students who have yet to sponsor a campus lecture.
<P>This may be <I>the </I>critical action you need to take to begin bringing conservative lecturers to your campus.
<P>Foundation staffers <B>Ron Robinson, Matthew Schenk, Michelle Sharp, Kristen 
Kingsley, Dan Flynn</B>, and <B>James Taylor </B>will be on hand to walk you through the steps you must take to hold a lecture and build a successful campus organization. 
<P>In coming months, Young America's Foundation is sponsoring <B>Clarence Thomas </B>at Southeast Missouri State University, <B>Jack Kemp </B>at Loyola University, <B>Ed Meese </B>at the University of Dayton-Law, and <B>Ralph Reed 
</B>at Hamilton College.  If you have wanted to bring speakers like these to your campus, but just didn't know how to go about it, then this seminar is for you!
<P>The one-day conference will be held at the Foundation's national headquarters in the Stranahan Conference Room on <B>Saturday, March 30</B>. Students must provide their own transportation to Northern Virginia. The Foundation will provide accommodations on Friday, March 22. 
<P>Space is limited for this special seminar. Reservations must be confirmed by calling <B>Michelle Sharp </B>at 1-800-292-9231. No more than two students per campus may attend.


<p><p><hr><center><P><a name="contact"></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]<P><h3>Contact Information</h3></center><p>Campus Leader is published by Young America's Foundation.<p>Address all editorial matter, free subscription inquiries, and changes ot address to Campus Leader, 110 Elden Street, Herndon, Virginia 22070.<p>Young America's Foundation was formed in order to provide essential conferences, seminars, educational materials, scholarships and speakers to the young people ot America. As an educational organization, the Foundation strives to acquaint American youth with the principles of American government and the genius of the American political system in order that they may have a fuller understanding of contemporary public policy questions.<p><p><p>[ <a href="home.html"> YAF Home</a> ]</body></html>

