<hr>
<center><a name="liddy"><h3>Liddy, O'Rourke, Mrs. Quayle, Snow<br>
Join Speakers Program</h3>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]
</center>
<p>
Young America's Foundation is pleased to announce that G. Gordon Liddy, P.J. O'Rourke, Tony Snow, 
and Marilyn Tucker Quayle have joined its speakers program.<p>

<b>G. Gordon Liddy</b> is the host of the hottest talk show in national syndication. He has firmly established himself as one of the most intelligent and engaging voices in the country. His triumphant return to the nation's capital also illustrates the significance of his central message: the importance of striving to prevail where others simply survive, whatever your field of endeavor.<p>

<b>P.J. O'Rourke</b> is called "the funniest writer in America" by the <i>Wall Street Journal</i>. At the lecture podium he never fails to inform and entertain, whether he is dealing with the state of the nation, the issues that shape our contemporary world, or the hilariously serious people who 
pontificate about them.<p>

<b>Marilyn Quayle</b>, wife of former Vice President Dan Quayle, is a partner in an Indianapolis law firm where she practices general corporate law, specializing in mergers and acquisitions, international, and health care law. During her husband's tenure as vice president, Mrs. Quayle served on the board of the Federal Emergency Management Agency. She was also chairman of the International Disaster Advisory Committee for the Agency for International Development. She continues to work with the National Cancer Institute as the national spokesman for NCI's Breast Cancer Summits.<p>

<b>Tony Snow</b> is a nationally syndicated columnist for the Detroit News and counterpoint columnist for <i>USA Today</i>. His editorials appear in various mediums around the world. He works as a commentator on National Public Radio and as a permanent guest-host on Rush Limbaugh's radio program. He is also a regular contributor to such television shows as <i>The McLaughlin Group, The McNeil-Lehrer News Hour, Good Morning America, Face the Nation</i>, and <i>Crossfire</i>.<p>

If you are interested in hosting one of these speakers, or any of our other speakers, please contact <b>Michelle Sharp</b> at 1-800-292-9231.
<p>

<p>
<hr>
<center>
<a name="short"><h3>Short, Griffin, Rosenberger Return to Foundation</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents </a>]
</center>
<p>
Fresh from Oliver North's exhilarating senatorial campaign where he served as director of the Virginia Finance Committee, <b>Marc Short</b> returns to Young America's Foundation as national director. Marc originally joined the Foundation as national director after graduating from Washington and Lee University in 1992. He will oversee the Foundation's 17th annual summer conference and explore new opportunities organizing regional conferences.<p>

<b>Kate Obenshain Griffln</b> concluded her tenure as Governor George Allen's special assistant for policy development and returned to the Foundation as director of program development. In 1991, after graduating from the University of Virginia, Kate became the Foundation's lecture director. She left the Foundation in the summer of 1993 to join Allen's gubernatorial campaign. After the election, she went to work for Governor Allen, focusing on education and health policy.<p>

In the midst of his high-profile Supreme Court case against the University of Virginia, <b>Ron Rosenberger</b> joins the Foundation as a program officer. Ron served as an intern at the Foundation while a student at the University of Virginia. As a campus activist at UVa, Ron founded a publication which was denied student activities funds on the basis of it being a "religious activity."  Ron filed suit against UVa and his case is currently before the Supreme Court. Ron was active with Young America's Foundation while at UVa, bringing prominent conservative speakers such as Edwin Meese and Dinesh D'Souza to campus.
<p>

<p>
<hr>
<center>
<a name="foundation"><h3>Foundation Rewards Activism and Scholarship</h3></a>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]
</center>
<p>
Young America's Foundation's mission is to encourage and assist future leaders who are struggling to acquire a solid, balanced education in the politically correct campus atmosphere. For those students who excel academically while striving to promote conservative causes on campus, the Foundation is proud to offer a limited number of annual scholarships.<p>

Scholarships will be awarded on the basis of three primary criteria: academic excellence, financial need, and the applicant's participation in Young America's Foundation's programs to promote balance and conservative activism on campus.<p>

Among the scholarships available are the <b>John Parker Memorial Scholarship</b>, the <b>John and Virginia Engalitcheff Scholarship</b> and the <b>Coleman-Timolat Scholarship</b>. If you are interested in receiving more information on our scholarship opportunities, please send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to the Scholarship Department, Young America's Foundation, 110 Elden Street, Herndon, Virginia 22070.
<p>

<p>
<hr>
<center>
<a name="thatcher"><h3> Thatcher, Keyes, Williams<br>
