<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<blockquote><blockquote>
<center>
<img alt="Beltway, U.S.A." src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/beltwayusa.gif">
<br><i>A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Financial issues facing America</i>
<p>


<h2>The Presidency is Ill</h2> 
<i>December 30, 1996</i>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<p>

As a child, I remember being caught with my hands in the cookie jar.  Most of us do.  The President on the other hand never learned his lesson and has been found, along with his associates, hiding in the Mrs. Fields cookie factory, and as a result is bringing down the Presidency and the whole country.
<P>
The President's damage control team has tried to dismiss any comparison between the President's indiscretions and those during the Watergate scandal.   I have to agree that there is little similarity between the two and this needs to be made clear. Clinton's transgressions are worse.  Another excuse that is commonly heard from the administration is "its just politics, and everyone does it."  All one must do is list the number of scandals such as troopergate, Whitewater, filegate, and lippogate, to realize that this administration has been in the cookie jar far more often than the last forty years of presidents. No other President has broken his word and abused the trust of the people more that the current President.
<P>
It is beyond my comprehension that our President has continually put himself in circumstances that ethical people would know to steer clear of.   People sometimes get caught up in a bad situation that they later regret, but no one can excuse the repeated indiscretions on the part of the administration. Claiming that it was a "bureaucratic SNAFU" once,will work, but a dozen of them is hard to accept.
<P>
If I were to try to come up with a list of illegal activities that a sitting president could do, I would be hard pressed to come up with a longer list than that of the current occupant of the White House.  Clinton has surrounded himself with selfish political operatives like himself  instead of competent people interested in the country rather than the next election cycle.  The American people are growing tired of politicians serving their own interests.  Being President of the United States should be an honor, and should be treated as such.  To often, politicians who have won election think they have been given a blank check that doesn't have to be cashed until the next election. The government derives its power from the governed and our trusted elected servants need to remember that.
<P>
All to often, politicians win merely because of a spending advantage or better campaign staffs, and then make the mistake that the American people understood their entire campaign platform and agree with its entire contents.  This was evident in 1992 and 1996.  In 1992, no one knew what Clinton was about, but they knew he was anything but George Bush.  Likewise, in 1996, Clinton had no agenda other than he would be less severe than the Republicans.  The President won the election, but he must remember that he will have to give the White House up in four years.  Will he leave the presidency in better or worse shape.  The trend is becoming obvious.
<P>
Isn't it time that the American public stop allowing our elected officials on both sides of the aisle to disparage our great nation.  Shouldn't we hold our elected officials up to a higher standard than we may hold ourselves or our neighbors. How we ever got to the point where we have accepted that our President is not in the least bit ethical, I don't know.
<P>
The sickness in the White House is spreading, and unfortunately, it is beginning to affect the very honor of the Presidency.  The White House is up for sale and the Lincoln bedroom is for rent to the highest bidder.  And the owner is a guy named "Bubba."





<p>
God bless you in your efforts,<p>
<center>
<img alt="Andrew Ingram" src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/sig.gif">
<p>
<br>
