<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<blockquote><blockquote>
<center>
<img alt="Beltway, U.S.A." src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/beltwayusa.gif">
<br><i>A daily look at the Moral, Ethical and Financial issues facing America</i>
<p>


<h2>Parents Get Side-Stepped Again</h2> 
<i>December 24, 1996</i>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<p>

Last week Jack Valente, the incredibly annoying and self-important president of the Motion Picture Association announced they he and the rest of the newly formed Television Council had finally reached agreement on a standard rating system for TV shows.  I give it a rating of "G" for garbage.
<P>
I was not overly excited when Congress and the President forced TV manufacturers to install V-Chips in all new TVs.  I feel that besides being an example of regulating us to death, It was also going to give parents a good excuse to leave their kids in front of the television and ignore their parental responsibilities.
<p>
But if the V-Chip is going to become a reality then it might as well be useful.  The garbage that the commission calls a rating system will do nothing for parents of children in all age ranges.  The primary problem is that the ratings are incredibly vague and don’t even cover news programs which I find often have the most violence and mature themes that we are trying to protect our children from.
<p>
Rather than make my point using shows like ABC’s NYPD which  we all regard as inappropriate for children, the focus should be on the middle of the road shows, and some shows which are supposedly family shows.  Because many shows will not be bad enough to warrant the most severe rating nor will they be timid enough to receive the "G" rating, a giant mushy middle will be left that will contain an incredibly large range of show content.
<p>
A good example of this problem is evident in the ABC Friday lineup of "family" shows.  ABC bills their Friday lineup as all family shows but quite often the theme becomes quite mature.  Issues such as dating, racism, religion and sex are common even in the family programs. Parents can not be sure that their favorite family show won’t end up showing a young boy and girl in a compromising situation. By then it is too late for the parent to intervene, and the parent must try to explain what happened.
<p>
The problem with the proposed system is that because of its vagueness, parents will not have any idea why a program received the rating it did.  It is because of this, that the rating system will be of little use to parents.  There is really no line that television won’t cross.  ABC even has a show about a teenage witch who often casts spells over her enemies.  As if  parents didn’t have enough working against them, news programs will be exempt from the ratings.  The thought that the evening news and even the tabloid shows like Hard Copy will not even be rated is quite ridiculous.
<p>
The television executives will tell me that I am a prude, and that a little kissing and  or witchcraft is okay for our children but I disagree and in the end, isn’t it the parents final decision what their children watch.  I plan to discuss sex and other mature issues when I feel it is appropriate, not when ABC, NBC, and CBS think so.
<p>
The new ratings system is just another case of the fox guarding the hen house. Groups like the Family Research Council and the Parents Television Council are pushing for giving parents more information to make there decisions.  Hopefully parents will get eventually get there due.
<p>
Until then, be careful.  You never know what is coming on the television next.


<p>
God bless you in your efforts,<p>
<center>
<img alt="Andrew Ingram" src="/townhall/columnists/ingram/sig.gif">
<p>
<br>
<p>
