<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Devine: Betting on Bob Dole -- 8/10/96 -- ACU </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>August 10, 1996</I><BR>
<CENTER>
<H2>Betting on Bob Dole</H2>
<B>Donald Devine</B>
</CENTER>
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
It is worry, worry, worry among the Chicken Littles on the right over Bob Dole's campaigning.  Everyone is in a panic.  But the sky is not falling.  In fact, victory is in the bag for Mr. Dole.  And we take our predictions seriously.  We were the first, on Nov. 22, 1994, to predict Bill Clinton's rejuvenation if the Republicans tried to govern from Congress, and we do not make prognostications lightly.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
We have the luxury of having been there before.  It is hard to recall, but in the summer of 1980 all the campaign and media talk was about Ronald Reagan being too old.  He made front-page "gaffs" almost daily.  As a result, a Gallup poll found Gov. Reagan behind President Carter 31 percent to 65 percent at the beginning of the year and as late as June trailed 32 percent to 37 percent for Mr. Carter and 24 percent for John Anderson.  On Aug. 18, 1980, it was Mr. Carter 39 percent, Mr. Reagan 38 percent and Mr. Anderson 14 percent.  Those in the campaign never felt comfortable that Mr. Reagan could win and the media were certain he could not.  Ours was a lonely voice in the campaign even to recommend that "the Gipper" debate Mr. Carter.  And that was the concern with a candidate later called "the Great Communicator."
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In other words, there is nothing new about panic over campaigns during the doldrums before the convention.  As far as dissatisfaction from the right, remember the grumbling among conservatives during the summer of 1998, some threatening a third party? Then George Bush promised at the convention that fulfilling the Reagan legacy was his "mission" and "read my lips, no new taxes."  After that, the right was won and enthustiastically worked for his election.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
This time Bob Dole won the nomination with a conservative appeal but reached out to moderates afterward.  That is because he knows two things.  It is smart politics now, and he knows that the platform will be conservative, the speeches and the convention acceptance will be too, as will be the vice-president, and so will the campaign and the ads.  It made sense to reach out to moderates now, before the dominant theme re-emerges. After all, what difference does a keynote speaker make?
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The desperate search for a new leader is ludicrous.  Where is one to look? To Congress? The panic on the Hill is manifest.  After more than a year of predicatbly foolish strategy, now it is everyone for himself on welfare, health, spending, legal services, affirmative action, minimum wage, etc.  Taking Medicaid -- the biggest part of welfare reform -- out of the bill so President Clinton can sign it is an outrageous elect Clinton-and-us-GOP-Congress strategy.  Or are we supposed to look to candidates that Mr. Dole defeated or who declined even to run against him?  They lost.  To Colin Powell as vice president?  That would simply increase the chorus for the presidential candidate to step down in his favor.  There, simply, is no magic solution, and one is not needed.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
How will Mr. Dole win? He starts with 37 percent, almost exactly what Mr. Reagan had at the same stage of the contest. Politics is a 40-40-20 proposition at the national level, 40 percent Democrats, 40 percent Republicans and 20 percent in the middle.  In a three-way race, solidifying the base gets almost to the victory line all by itself.  The only real problem in the polls now for Mr. Dole is his weakness with the GOP base.  Depending on the poll, he wins only 61 to 70 percent of Republicans, when he needs 85 percent.  That present weakness translates to strength when Mr. Dole convinces the 85 percent at the convention with a strong issue appeal.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
What about the problem with women?  The Linda Divall-American Viewpoint poll shows this is almost exclusively a problem with older women.  For both older men and women, Mr. Dole must respons successfully on Medicare.  But he needs funds that are not available now to do so.  The real problem is younger men.  For both younger men and women, he needs a strong anti-tax, pro-jobs/growth plan.  These will come.  The good news is the problem is not abortion nor the social issues.  For people who will cast their vote on these issues, these are still a net positive for Republicans.  For abortion, a Wirthlin poll shows that 26 percent of voters say their ballots will be influenced by this issue -- and 17 percent are pro-life and 9 percent pro-choice.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
With these bases covered, there is one important latent aspect to the campaign -- as there was in 1980 -- the good citizen who loves his country.  Mr. Clinton's support is artificially high today because that voter still looks at him and sees the president of the United States of America.  After the Democratic National Convention, he is Candidate Clinton.  Come Election Day, voters will go to the polls thinking, "He is a caring young man and he tries, but I just cannot see the presidency dragged through the courts for the next four years on sexual harassment, Arkansas cronies, land deals, cattle futures and the rest.  Bob Dole is a good man and I will support him."  This will be especially important for three-fourths of Ross Perot-leaning voters who are male, as it was for a similar group regarding the hostage crisis in Iran in 1980.  Mr. Perot will be left with liberal-leaning people who do not like the incumbent -- as Mr. Anderson was -- and Mr. Dole will win.
<P>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Mr. Clinton will be like Mr. Carter in 1980 -- it will be late, but support will dive quickly.  It will be all over, and there will be President Dole.  It is in the bag.
<P><P>
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER>[ <A HREF="/conservative/I-col.html">ACU Columnists</A> | <A HREF="/conservative/welcome.html">ACU Home</A> ]<P>
</CENTER><P>
